From interogating the real - why is hegel lacanian:
In the domain of knowledge, we encounter this logic of separation when, all of a sudden, we see that what we thougt was the limitation of out knowledge about the thing is in fact an inherent limitation of the thin itself. Recall Adorno's analysis of the antagonistic character of the notion of society. In the social sciences, the notion of society oscilattes between two extremes. Either we conceive of it in terma of Anglo-Saxon individualistic-nominalism, as a composite of ineracting individuals as the only really existing agents, or else we adopt a more Continental perspective, exemplified by the work of Emile Durkheim, and conceive of society as an organic Whole, a totality that pre-exists idividuals. The atagonism is here irreducable, and we seem to be dealing with a true Kantian antinomy (the existence of two mutually exclusive, vontradictory even, claims that are both equally justified) which cannot be resolvedthrough any higher dialectical synthesis: society as such cannot but appear as a Thing-in-itself, forever out of grasp of our cognitive capacities. However, as a different approach, one should merely observe the way that this radical antinomy, which seems to preclude our access to the Thing, is already at work in the Thing itself: the fundamental feature of today's society is the irreconcilable atagonism between social totality and idividuals. What first appeared as the sign of our inability to understand what society really is tutns out to be the fundamental feature of social reality itself. That is to say, initially, we were 'alienated', our limited knowledge prewented us from achieving a notion of society; then, in a properly dialectical reversal, this limitation proved to indicate the antagonism of society as such.
Buddhist Ethics: In the Gnostic mode, for Buddhism, ethics is ultimately a question of knowledge and ignorance: our craving (desire) - our attachment to terrestrial goods - is conditioned by our ignorance, so that deliverance comes from proper knowing. What Christion love means is that, on the contrary, there is a decision not grounded in (true or false) knowledge- Christianity thus breaks with the entire tradition of the primacy of knowledhe that spans from Buddhism through gnosticism to Spinoza.
Buddhism/Psychoanalisis/Hegel: In what , then, does the gap that forever separates psychoanalysis from Buddhism consists? In order to answer this question, e should confront the basic enigma of Buddhism, its blind spot: how did the fall into samsara, the Wheel of Life, occur? This question is, of course, the exact opposite of the stabdard Buddhist concern: how can we break out of the Whel of Life and attain nirvana? (This shift is homologours to Hegel's reversal of the classic metaphysical question, how can we penetrate through false apperances to their underlying essentil reality? For Hegel, the question is, on the contrary, how has apperance emerged out of reality?) The nature and origin of the impetus by means of wich desire, its deception, emerged from the Boid, is the great unknown at hte heart of the Buddhist edifice: it points toward an act that 'braksr the symmetry' within nirvana itself and thus makes something appear out of nothing (another analogy with quantum physics, with its notion of braking the symmetry). The Freudian answer is drive: wat Freud calls Trieb is not, as it may appear, the Buddhist Wheel of Life, the craving that enslaves us to the world of illusions. Drive, on the ontrary, goes on even when the subhect has 'traversed the fantasy' and broken out of the illusory craving for the (lost) object of desire.
Death drive/nirvana principle: This is wat Lacan aims at when ke empasizes tha difference between the Freudian death dive and the so-called 'nirvana principle', acording to which every life system tends toward wquilibrium, the lowest level of energy, and ultimately toeard death. 'Nothingness" (the void, being deprve of all substance) and the lowet level of enrgy paradoxically no longer coincide; it is 'cheaper' (it cost the system less energy) to persist in 'something' than to dwell in nothng', at the lowest level of tension, or in the void, the dissolution of all order. It is this distance tht sustains the death drive (i.e. drive as such, since as Lacan puts it, 'every drive is virtualy a death drive'): far from being the same tension, the longing for return to original nothingness), death drive is the tension that persists and insists beyond and against the nirvana principle (the sriving toward the  dissolution of all tension, the longing for return to original nothingness), death drive is the tension that persists and insists beyond and against the nirvana principle. In other words, far from being opposed to the pleasure principle, tne nirvana principle is its highest and most radical expression. In this precise sense, death drive stand for its exact opposite, for the dimension of the 'undead', of a spectral life that insists beyond (biological) death.
Islam: Thus us why psychoanalysis is firmly entrenched in the Western Judeo-christian tradition, as opposed, not only to Orientl spirituality, but also the Islam - one of the religions of the Book, which , like Oriental spirituality, endorses the notion of the ultimate vanity, illusory nature, of every object of desire.
Lacan: Mantaining the gap that forever sepaates every emirical ('pathological') object of desire from its 'impossible' object-cause whose place must remain empty? Is not what Lacan calls 'symbolic castration' this very gap which reners every emorocal object unsatisfctory?
Lacan: Absolute Knowledge is not accomplishd symbolization.
Crusades: In order for us to experience the spiritual truth of Christianity one must first occupy the tomb and then ecperience its emptiness - it is only through this disappointment, through this failure-in-triumph, that one gains insight into how, in order to -live in Christ; one does not have to go far away and occupy empty tombs, since Christ is already here whenever there is love between his followers.

