Answers:
-Troika: Not "Being qua being as generic multiplicity"
-For Badiou "one" comes secondary. One is an operation, one is an effect of couting, while multiplicity is there from the begining (multiplicity and void and all that)
-For Alenka and Zizek, there is no original multiplicity, and this absence is iscribed into multiplicity from very begining (multiplicity is multiplicity withouth one) -> The one as absence is already here. (One as failed, as impossible)
-Alenka: There is multiplicity because one can not be one.
-Freud (small remark): Multiplicity in dreams is always a sign of castration (if you dream many faluses, it means you dont have one) -> Zizek: Present multiplicity is always sign of blocke/sabotaged one.
-We are tempted to isist on this primacy of the cut/barbed one, of the impossible one. That the one is as it were ..(there us (troika) get really hegelian).. that there are ones of course, but the existing ones are a echo of their own imposibility (as it were). In a certain way Alain is right: What is, is always originaly multiplicity, but why do we then start to count to one? Precisely by the lack or impossibility of the one.
-Badiou: There is multiplicity in logics of the world, and then, I don't know from where all of a suden there are worlds. I know he would probably reject this as a question, but what I am always asking him is: Why does "Being qua being" (this prerepresentable multiplicity), why does it organise itself into worlds? -Worlds are in a way worlds which appear. Worlds are modes of transcedential apperance.. -Alenka solution: Already multiplicity from the verry begining is the multiplicity, because one is impossible. That this is the answer why multiplicity precisely to fil in this gap, has to aprear (to itself).
-For Hegel true enigma is: (not Kantian: We live in apparances, can we reach the thing in itself (the real)) Ok, there is being, multipicity out there, but why does being start to appear to itself?
-Badiou (too much of the dialectical materialist) vs Zizek (transcendentalist) true fight: Apropo world, the status of the world. Zizek: All the coordinates are already the coordinates of subjective, of universe of (naively) "simbolic universe with subjectivity included" -> there is no world outside language and subject. Badiou insists that world is just a category of what (Engels?) would have called dialectics in nature. If you look at nature: animals, rocks, group of stars; all this can be a world. -> Zizek doubts if this is a legitimate move.
-For Lacan existance (transcendential determination) is absolutely not the same as being. -> In Hegel existence is being which is apperance of some essence. -> For existence you already have to have an essence. 
	*For Lacan neither subject, neither woman exist. (Not to say that there are no woman!) -> There is no big other (He doesent only say that the big other doesent exist!) 
	*What doesent exist insist? (Drive doesent exist, but the very definition of a drive is that it insists.) -> Subject dosent exist, it just leaves traces in existence.
-Distinction between (in strict lacanian terms) apperance and phenomenon: Apperance being apperance of something, and phenomenon being apperance of nothing. -> (Just raises desire for something behind, but ther is nothing behind) apperance is the abbys.


